## Summary of all changes

| File | Change | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Navigation.module.scss` | `.navInner` → `flex-wrap: nowrap` | Prevents logo from ever occupying row 2 |
| `Navigation.module.scss` | `.logo` → `display: flex` (was `inline-flex`) + `min-width: max-content` | Closes the two gaps that `flex-shrink: 0` alone doesn't cover |
| `docs/design-anti-patterns.md` | AP-066 fleshed out with the four-property lock + yield-surface model | Codifies the principle so it's enforced on every future nav touch |
| `docs/design/navigation.md` | New §4.7 with priority hierarchy table + identity lock spec | Makes the priority rule findable by any agent working on the nav |

---

## Principle

**AP-066 — Identity Lock.** A site name is not a flex child like any other — it is the minimum viable signal of who this site belongs to. The correct mental model is not "give it high priority in the flex algorithm" but "remove it from the flex compression budget entirely." That requires all four properties working together: `display: flex` (not `inline-flex`), `flex-shrink: 0`, `min-width: max-content`, and `white-space: nowrap` on the text node. Designate an explicit yield surface on the other side of the nav row — the tagline is the correct candidate because secondary context can wrap without communicating failure, while the name wrapping always communicates broken layout. The logo never compromises. The tagline always does.
